<article class="journal-post">
  <div class="journal-post__inner">

    <p class="journal-post__lead">When we drafted the Mira, we kept asking ourselves: how many ways could one piece work? Turns out, a lot. Here are three ways our team is wearing her this month.</p>

    <p>The Mira sits in that rare category of pieces that genuinely move between contexts — desk to dinner, school run to friend’s wedding — without ever feeling forced. The trick is in the drape: a slight gather at the waist that flatters without clinging, a length that hits the calf at exactly the right place, and a neckline that frames without exposing.</p>

    <h2>1. The everyday </h2>

    <p>Pair the Mira in oat with white sneakers, a tonal cashmere wrap thrown over the shoulders, and a structured tote in cognac leather. The combination is decidedly weekend but elegant enough for a 10 AM meeting at a café.</p>

    <p>Keep the jewellery minimal — a single gold cuff, no earrings, hair down.</p>

    <blockquote class="journal-post__quote">
      <p>"The first time I tried it on, I knew this was going to be the dress I reach for when I haven’t had time to think about what to wear."</p>
      <cite>— Reem, our pattern cutter</cite>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>2. The evening</h2>

    <p>Same dress, entirely different mood. Switch to the silver Mira variant. Add the Crescent Drop Earrings and a slim black belt at the waist to define. Strappy gold heels, hair pulled into a low chignon.</p>

    <p>The drape catches the light differently after dusk — you’ll see it in restaurant photos.</p>

